{
  "chapter": {
    "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10",
    "translationId": "lxxe",
    "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
    "chapterNumber": 10,
    "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10",
    "summary": "Source text for Ecclesiastes 10 in Brenton's English Septuagint."
  },
  "verses": [
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.1",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 1,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:1",
      "text": "Pestilent flies will corrupt a preparation of sweet ointment: and a little wisdom is more precious than great glory of folly.",
      "paragraphStart": true
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.2",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 2,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:2",
      "text": "A wise man’s heart is at his right hand; but a fool’s heart at his left.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.3",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 3,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:3",
      "text": "Yea, and whenever a fool walks by the way, his heart will fail him, and all that he thinks of is folly.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.4",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 4,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:4",
      "text": "If the spirit of the ruler rise up against thee, leave not thy place; for soothing will put an end to great offences.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.5",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 5,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:5",
      "text": "There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, wherein an error has proceeded from the ruler.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.6",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 6,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:6",
      "text": "The fool has been set in very high places, while rich men would sit in a low one.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.7",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 7,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:7",
      "text": "I have seen servants upon horses, and princes walking as servants on the earth.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.8",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 8,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:8",
      "text": "He that digs a pit shall fall into it; and him that breaks down a hedge a serpent shall bite.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.9",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 9,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:9",
      "text": "He that removes stones shall be troubled thereby; he that cleaves wood shall be endangered thereby.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.10",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 10,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:10",
      "text": "If the axe-head should fall off, then the man troubles his countenance, and he must put forth more strength: and in that case skill is of no advantage to a man.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.11",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 11,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:11",
      "text": "If a serpent bite when there is no charmer’s whisper, then there is no advantage to the charmer.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.12",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 12,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:12",
      "text": "The words of a wise mouth are gracious: but the lips of a fool will swallow him up.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.13",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 13,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:13",
      "text": "The beginning of the words of his mouth is folly: and the end of his talk mischievous madness.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.14",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 14,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:14",
      "text": "A fool moreover multiplies words: man knows not what has been, nor what will be: who shall tell him what will come after him?",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.15",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 15,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:15",
      "text": "The labour of fools will afflict them, as that of one who knows not to go to the city.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.16",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 16,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:16",
      "text": "Woe to thee, O city, whose king is young, and thy princes eat in the morning!",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.17",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 17,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:17",
      "text": "Blessed art thou, O land, whose king is a son of nobles, and whose princes shall eat seasonably, for strength, and shall not be ashamed.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.18",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 18,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:18",
      "text": "By slothful neglect a building will be brought low: and by idleness of the hands the house will fall to pieces.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.19",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 19,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:19",
      "text": "Men prepare bread for laughter, and wine and oil that the living should rejoice: but to money all things will humbly yield obedience.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    },
    {
      "id": "lxxe:ecclesiastes.10.20",
      "translationId": "lxxe",
      "bookSlug": "ecclesiastes",
      "chapterNumber": 10,
      "verseNumber": 20,
      "referenceLabel": "Ecclesiastes 10:20",
      "text": "Even in thy conscience, curse not the king; and curse not the rich in thy bedchamber: for a bird of the air shall carry thy voice, and that which has wings shall report thy speech.",
      "paragraphStart": false
    }
  ]
}
